# KIP-500 — Replace ZooKeeper with a Self-Managed Metadata Quorum

> Notes on the Kafka Improvement Proposal by Colin McCabe (2019, status: Accepted).
> Source: https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/KAFKA/KIP-500
> Scope here: Motivation + Architecture/design overview.
> Note the KIP is deliberately a *vision document* — it leaves out RPC formats and on-disk
> formats, deferring those to follow-on KIPs (595, 631, and friends).

---

## 1. Motivation

Two goals, stated plainly at the top: **manage metadata more scalably and robustly (to support
far more partitions)**, and **simplify deployment and configuration**. Everything else follows
from those.

### 1.1 The deep problem: Kafka didn't eat its own dog food

The KIP opens with a lovely bit of self-criticism. Kafka spends its entire existence telling
users that **state should be managed as a stream of events** — a single offset describes your
position, consumers catch up by replaying, and the log gives you a clean total order so
everyone moves along **one timeline**.

**Kafka itself did not do this with its own metadata.** It treated metadata changes as
isolated, unrelated mutations.

Concretely, in the ZooKeeper world:

- The controller **pushes** state-change notifications (`LeaderAndIsr`, `UpdateMetadata`) out to
  brokers. A broker can **receive some of these changes but not others**. The controller retries
  a few times and then **gives up** — leaving brokers in a **divergent state**. There's no
  offset, no ordering, no way to detect the gap.
- **The controller's in-memory state and the ZooKeeper state routinely disagree.** ZK is
  nominally the store of record, but when a partition leader updates its ISR directly in ZK,
  the controller often doesn't learn about it for *many seconds*.
- **ZooKeeper watches are a bad event-log substitute.** They're one-shot, and the number you can
  set is limited for performance reasons. When a watch fires, it tells you only *"something
  changed"* — not *what*. By the time the controller re-reads the znode and re-arms the watch,
  the state may have changed again. If no watch is set, the change may be **missed entirely**.
- In some cases, **restarting the controller was the only way to fix the discrepancy.** (If
  you've operated Kafka, this line lands.)

**The fix, stated as a principle:** *store metadata in Kafka itself, as an event log.* Brokers
stop being pushed at and start **consuming metadata events** — which means changes always arrive
**in the same order**, gaps are impossible (you have an offset), and a broker can cache metadata
in a local file and on restart **only fetch the delta**, not the entire cluster state. That
delta-based catch-up is the thing that unlocks *far more partitions with less CPU*.

### 1.2 The shallow-but-real problem: two systems is one too many

- ZooKeeper is a **separate system** with its own config syntax, tooling, and deployment
  patterns. Operators must learn to run **two** distributed systems to run one.
- **Security is easy to get wrong** precisely *because* the configs are separate. The KIP's
  example: an admin configures SASL on Kafka, believes the cluster is secured — and hasn't
  realized ZooKeeper needs its own, separate security configuration. Unifying gives one
  security model.
- Removing the dependency makes a **single-node Kafka** possible, which is great for someone
  who just wants to try Kafka without standing up multiple daemons.

