## 5. Where the details actually live (follow-on KIPs)

KIP-500 is the vision; these are the specs:

- **KIP-595 — A Raft Protocol for the Metadata Quorum** ← *the actual Raft implementation*
- **KIP-631 — The Quorum-based Kafka Controller**
- KIP-455 (replica reassignment API), KIP-497 (inter-broker AlterISR API),
  KIP-543 / KIP-555 (de-ZooKeeper-ing the tools), KIP-589, KIP-590 (redirect ZK mutations to
  the controller)

The KIP explicitly cites **Ongaro & Ousterhout's Raft paper**, plus HDFS and Microsoft's **Tango**
("Distributed Data Structures over a Shared Log") — the latter being the intellectual ancestor of
"model your system's state as a shared log."

---

## 6. Where things ended up (post-KIP reality, as of 2026)

- KRaft was declared **production-ready in Kafka 3.3.1**, and **ZooKeeper support was removed
  entirely in Kafka 4.0** — KRaft is now the only supported mode.
- The metadata log lives in an internal topic: **`__cluster_metadata`**. Because it's a Kafka
  topic, you can inspect and replay it with ordinary Kafka tooling — a nice side effect of the
  "metadata as an event log" bet.
- **Controller failover went from seconds to milliseconds**, exactly as the KIP predicted, because
  standby controllers are already warm.

