## 7. How this connects to the Raft notes

If you've read the Raft paper, KRaft maps onto it directly — with **one deliberate inversion**:

| Raft (paper) | KRaft |
|---|---|
| Leader **pushes** `AppendEntries` to followers | Controller followers and **brokers pull** via fetch |
| Heartbeat = empty `AppendEntries` | Heartbeat = the **`MetadataFetch` itself** |
| Log = generic replicated log | Log = a real Kafka topic (`__cluster_metadata`) |
| Snapshot + `InstallSnapshot` RPC | Metadata snapshots; full-image send if a broker is too far behind |
| Commit = replicated to majority | Same — majority of controllers |
| `2f+1` tolerates `f` failures | Same: 3 controllers → 1 failure, 5 → 2 |

**The push→pull inversion is the thing to be able to explain.** Kafka already had a
battle-hardened, high-performance **pull-based replication engine** (that's how every consumer
and every follower replica works). Rather than bolt a second, push-based replication mechanism
onto the side, KRaft reuses the one Kafka already had — which is also why the metadata log can
just *be* a topic.

**Interview line:** *"KRaft is Raft with the arrows reversed — followers and brokers fetch from
the leader by offset, which lets Kafka reuse its existing pull-based replication and makes the
metadata log a first-class Kafka topic."*